      <scopecontent id="aspace_a74133f4172942c95aed6ccb8066bf04">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The records consist of memoranda, minutes, public opinion surveys, and reports documenting Allen Grover's role as Associate Director in the Office of Facts and Figures (OFF). The OFF was established in October 1941 by Franklin Delano Roosevelt (FDR) in order to disseminate information to the American public regarding the war effort. On 13 June 1942 FDR established the Office of War Information, which subsumed the OFF and included the Committee on War Information Policy, of which Grover was a member.</p>
         <p>The records notably document the U.S. Government's policy during World War II on information dissemination, propaganda, public opinion, and the concerns for the "post-war world order." A small amount of subject files contains organizational charts, printed ephemera, and materials on topics including rubber production and press monitoring.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_cbf68596a87ff5a99cc279cee0748677">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Allen Grover (James Allen Grover) was born in St. Louis, Missouri, on August 4, 1900. He graduated from Yale in 1922. He held positions at United American Steamship Lines, and at the brokerage firms of J. G. White &amp; Company and Pynchon &amp; Company. In 1931, Grover became a contributing editor for business and finance at <title render="italic">
               <part>Time</part>
            </title> magazine. The following year he transferred to <title render="italic">
               <part>Fortune</part>
            </title> and eventually rose to assistant managing editor. In 1936, Grover became personal assistant to Henry Luce, the head of Time, Inc., and in 1939 was promoted to vice president. In December 1941 Grover joined the U.S. Government Office of Facts and Figures, which became the Office of War Information in June 1942, with a six-month contract as Associate Director under Archibald MacLeish. He left in early July 1942 and returned to Time. Grover retired in 1962 from Time, and died in New York City on May 3, 1993.</p>  
      </bioghist>
  
